<tr>
  <td class="diff-marker">&#160;</td>
  <td class="diff-context"><div>{{main|Canadian Indian residential school system}}</div></td>
  <td class="diff-marker">&#160;</td>
  <td class="diff-context"><div>{{main|Canadian Indian residential school system}}</div></td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td class="diff-marker">−</td>
  <td class="diff-deletedline"><div>An 1884 amendment to the Act mandated education for Indian children, to bring them to read and write English.  A defensive posture for those who wished to remain of Indian status was therefore to remain illiterate.  The [[Canadian Indian residential school system]] can be seen as an attempt to force Indians off their lands, sever family ties and diminish traditional Indian culture<del class="diffchange diffchange-inline">, and one can readily envision the trouble between residential school teachers and their students</del>, for which on 11 June 2008 the government of Canada apologized.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|author = CTV News|title = Harper apologizes for residential school abuse|publisher = CTV|url = http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20080610/native_apology_080611/20080611?hub=TopStories|date = 2008-06-11}}&lt;/ref&gt;</div></td>
  <td class="diff-marker">+</td>
  <td class="diff-addedline"><div>An 1884 amendment to the Act mandated education for Indian children, to bring them to read and write English.  A defensive posture for those who wished to remain of Indian status was therefore to remain illiterate.  The [[Canadian Indian residential school system]] can be seen as an attempt to force Indians off their lands, sever family ties and diminish traditional Indian culture, for which on 11 June 2008 the government of Canada apologized.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|author = CTV News|title = Harper apologizes for residential school abuse|publisher = CTV|url = http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20080610/native_apology_080611/20080611?hub=TopStories|date = 2008-06-11}}&lt;/ref&gt;</div></td>
</tr>
